<HEADLINE>
FT  30 SEP 94 / Markets hit by US data and Alcatel results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial markets in Europe and the US fell sharply yesterday after figures
showing strong US economic growth and weak results from a leading European
industrial group.
In the US, an upward final revision to second-quarter gross domestic product
growth to 4.1 per cent year on year from 3.8 per cent, together with a
lower-than-expected figure for weekly jobless claims, pushed the 30-year US
Treasury bond yield to touch a 2 1/4 year high of 7.87 per cent in early US
trading.
Analysts said bond investors feared that the Federal Reserve's decision this
week to keep interest rates at their current level meant the authorities
were not acting fast enough to keep inflation under control.
'The markets are increasingly of the opinion that Mr Greenspan (the Federal
Reserve chairman) hasn't got a grip,' said Mr Keith Skeoch, chief economist
at broker James Capel.
The fall in Treasury bonds depressed US equities, with the Dow Jones
Industrial average closing 23.55 points lower at 3,854.63.
European markets were already fearful that the downward trend in European
interest rates had ended, and the weakness in US shares and bonds reinforced
problems in futures and equity markets. Shares in Alcatel Alsthom, the big
French industrial group, fell 13.8 per cent to FFr488.7 after a warning of a
sharp drop in annual profits.
The decline in the shares in the telecoms, transport and engineering group
depressed Paris stocks and the CAC-40 index closed 1.5 per cent lower. In
Germany it contributed to the 3.9 per cent decline in the shares of Siemens,
a quarter of whose turnover comes from telecommunications equipment.
In London, the FT-SE 100 index closed 46.2 points or 1.5 per cent lower at
2,992.5.
