<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / National &amp; Provincial ousts chief executive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David O'Brien resigned yesterday as chief executive of National &amp;
Provincial Building Society, after being told that the board wanted to
replace him with the society's finance director.
His successor is Mr Alistair Lyons, aged 40, who was brought into N&amp;P as
finance director by Mr O'Brien soon after his own arrival four years ago.
'We really felt we were moving from a stage where David's skills were very
valuable to a stage where Alistair's would be more appropriate,' Lord
Shuttleworth, N&amp;P chairman, said. 'When I communicated this to David, he
decided to resign.'
Mr O'Brien had a strikingly unconventional style of management in a sector
which is noted for a more traditional approach. Last year a clash of
cultures was cited as the reason for the collapse of the planned merger
between N&amp;P and Leeds Permanent, which would have created the UK's third
largest society.
In 1990 he had started a programme to re-design the society's operations,
and had developed a style based on teamwork and emphasising the focus on the
customer rather than the product. While he is widely credited for turning
around the performance of a society which had been in some difficulties
before his arrival, he was also seen as someone who created a potentially
unsettling climate of constant change.
N&amp;P's pre-tax profits increased 51 per cent in 1993 to reach Pounds 121m,
but at the same time its cost/income ratio rose sharply at a time when some
other large societies were seeing the ratio fall or remain broadly stable.
Lord Shuttleworth said N&amp;P, the eighth largest society, had gone through a
considerable time of change and saw the next stage as one of 'implementation
and consolidation of what we had achieved'.
Mr Lyons played down suggestions that his appointment would mark a
significant shift in direction for N&amp;P, but said he expected the pace of
change to be slower in future. Most of the building blocks for the society
to provide a wide range of financial services had already been put in place,
he said.
Mr O'Brien's abrupt departure means that he will qualify for severance pay
in compensation for loss of office, but the society said details had not
been agreed.
</TEXT>
