<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Managers 'fail to stem car as perk'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Managements seeking to dispense with the company car are offering too little
in cash alternatives, a report says today.
The report by Wyatt, consultants and actuaries, found that in spite of tax
changes that reduced the value of a car as a company perk, 95 per cent of
employers were offering company cars compared to 98 per cent a year ago.
About 46 per cent of employers running company cars used lease or contract
hire cars while 54 per cent bought them.
The report says that more companies are trying to buy back company cars with
cash alternatives - 39 per cent of the 264 organisations in the study
compared with 28 per cent last year.
But take-up of the cash alternatives was low - only 10 per cent. Wyatt
suggests this was because employers were offering too little as an
alternative. Mr Mike Landon, senior consultant at Wyatt, said the average
alternative on a car valued at Pounds 20,000 was Pounds 6,000 a year.
He said: 'An employee would need Pounds 10,000 to operate the same car out
of after-tax earnings without being worse off, which explains why most have
decided to stick with their cars.'
Another cash alternative under consideration by many employers is the
adoption of flexible benefits schemes, enabling employees to choose a
variety of benefits in exchange for part of their pay.
Only 5 per cent of the employers in the survey had introduced such schemes,
but half of those had done so in the last 12 months. Of employers who did
not operate a flexible benefits scheme, more than 40 per cent were
considering doing so, although administration was regarded as a barrier.
Company Cars and Flexible Benefits. The Wyatt Company (UK), 21 Tothill
Street, London. Pounds 120.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
