<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Tax 'widens savings gulf': Research indicates concessions
aid rich and exacerbate inequalities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The distribution of wealth across the UK is extremely unequal, with most
households having no substantial savings other than their houses and
pensions, an economic study has shown.
A further factor that may exacerbate inequalities is that the savings of the
poor are apt to be taxed more than those of the rich, the research suggests.
The study, by the Institute for Fiscal Studies for the Joseph Rowntree
Foundation, says the tax discrepancy is due to the different savings methods
used by the rich and poor.
According to the survey, the average amount of wealth held by households is
about Pounds 3,000, excluding pensions and housing. This overall figure is
skewed by a small number of very wealthy individuals - about half the
households have savings of less than Pounds 450, the report notes.
Poorer households tend to attract higher rates of taxation, primarily
because their savings are concentrated in interest-bearing accounts at banks
and building societies that are taxed more heavily than other forms of
wealth.
The poorer half of the population, for example, holds some 60 per cent of
its assets in interest-bearing accounts.
The richest part of the population, by contrast, holds much of its wealth in
specialised financial assets which are given generous tax treatment. Shares,
personal equity plans and other investments such as unit trusts account for
about half the savings of the richest 5 per cent.
The report, which drew on a five-year research programme by NOP involving
almost 20,000 individuals, notes that this profile has shifted slightly in
recent years, with a fall in the proportion holding interest-bearing
accounts.
Meanwhile, measures of wealth that include housing and pension funds show a
more equal distribution pattern, partly because many owner-occupiers with
low financial wealth benefited from house-price rises in the 1980s, the
report adds.
However, the institute concludes: 'Stocks of housing and pension wealth are
the most important - often only - forms of wealth for most households. Only
the minority of households have enough liquid financial wealth to provide
for unexpected hardship, such as unemployment, before they actually retire.'
The Distribution of Wealth in the UK. IFS, 7 Ridgemount Street, London WC1E
7AE. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
