<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Bucket shops may gain rules leeway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Civil Aviation Authority is considering scaling down plans to regulate
airline ticket 'bucket shops' in spite of support for tougher legislation
from consumer bodies and trading standards officers.
The authority proposed in June that anyone other than an airline who
accepted payment for air travel would either have to produce a ticket
immediately or show that it had an Air Travel Organiser's Licence.
The shops, which sell airline tickets at a discount, told the authority they
would have difficulty meeting the licensing requirements. The tougher
proposals were supported by tour operators, consumers bodies and trading
standards officers.
The authority said it was now considering granting bucket shops licences
under less onerous conditions than those which have to be met by tour
operators. To receive a licence, tour operators have to arrange a bond
equivalent of between 10 per cent and 15 per cent of their turnover. The
bond is used to compensate customers if the operator goes out of business.
The authority said that if airlines were prepared to undertake to honour
tickets once they had been issued by bucket shops, the shops could arrange
bonds of about one-third of those required from tour operators.
The authority said it would also be prepared to grant a special class of
licence to air ticket vendors without a bond. It would only do this,
however, if airlines selling through these vendors entered into a legally
binding agreement with the authority to honour tickets.
</TEXT>
