<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Public funds are speeded up to help rescue private hospital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A private hospital set up to cater for patients from overseas has been saved
from the brink of receivership by its bankers and by the Scottish Office
only three months after opening.
One lender to Health Care International, a Pounds 180m hospital at Clydebank
near Glasgow, is understood to have become alarmed at the small number of
patients being treated in the hospital. A consortium of banks agreed two
weeks ago, however, to advance more money and the Scottish Office speeded up
payment of a grant to ensure the company's survival.
Labour last night demanded a Commons select committee investigation into the
government's role in funding the hospital. Unison, the public-sector union,
also demanded an inquiry.
About Pounds 29m in public funding has been paid or committed to the
project, including regional selective assistance, capital allowances due to
its construction in an enterprise zone, and loans and equity from Scottish
Enterprise, the development body.
In addition, Pounds 9.3m was spent by the Scottish Development Agency on
clearing the site, which had been contaminated with asbestos.
The 260-bed hospital offers acute treatment to patients who are unable
easily to obtain treatment in their home countries and who cannot afford to
go to the US for treatment. The project was conceived by two Harvard
professors, Dr Angelo Eraklis and Dr Raphael Levey, who obtained equity and
loan financing through the City of London.
It is understood that ING Bank, one of the leading banks in the Netherlands,
became alarmed at the hospital's trading position since its opening in June.
The fear that it might put the company into receivership led to concerted
action by the other banks in the lending syndicate to save the company.
The syndicate, which had advanced a total of Pounds 90m, made more funds
available to HCI. Its other members are Samuel Montagu, Midland Bank, Credit
Lyonnais and Royal Bank of Scotland.
HCI is trying to raise a further Pounds 15m in equity by October 14 to
reassure the banks.
HCI said it approached its equity investors three months ago for money in
addition to the Pounds 35m already invested, in order to strengthen the
balance sheet and fund other projects abroad.
The equity investors are led by Harvard Management, which invests money for
Harvard University. Others are Montgomery Medical Ventures, Samuel Montagu,
John Laing, Abu Dhabi Investment Company, British Aerospace and Drake &amp;
Scull.
Mr Andrew Gordon, one of the hospital's executive directors, said: 'We have
nothing to fear from any investigation of the support the government had
given us, which is completely above board.'
He confirmed that the venture had decided to seek an extra Pounds 15m but
denied that it had been thrown into crisis by a shortage of patients.
Mr Gordon said: 'We are either bang on or fractionally ahead of our budget
for patient admissions. That is not to say we are full, but we did not
expect the build-up to be quick.'
</TEXT>
