<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Cost liability urged for quango members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A call for quango board members to be made personally liable for costs if
they act in unlawful ways which have a financial effect on their agency, was
made yesterday.
Local government leaders from the West Midlands said quango board members
should be liable in the same way as local councillors.
Mr Brian Clack, leader of Coventry City Council, pointed out that quangos
spend Pounds 50bn of public money a year. He said: 'We should know much more
about how this money is spent and how we, as elected members, can call to
account these local quangos.'
He and other West Midlands metropolitan authority leaders yesterday
published a 10-point code of good practice which they urged the government
to have adopted by quangos, the agencies appointed and often financed by
Whitehall.
The code, based on a University of Central England study of practice among
quangos in the West Midlands, was published at the annual conference of the
Association of Metropolitan Authorities in Newcastle upon Tyne.
The council leaders want the ombudsman system to cover quangos. They also
want quangos to conduct their financial affairs in line with the principles
the Audit Commission applies to local government.
The proposed charter suggests quangos should make a commitment to open
meetings of their boards, adopt a complaints procedure, publish a list of
board members' pecuniary interests and appoint a monitoring officer to
ensure compliance with the law.
Appointed Agencies and Public Accountability. Dudley MBC, Council House,
Priory Road, Dudley, West Midlands DY1 1HF. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
