<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Satellite group aims up-market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eutelsat, the European satellite organisation, is planning to target the UK
in a campaign designed to take satellite television more up-market.
Until now the British market has been dominated by channels on the Astra
satellite system, particularly the subscription channels of British Sky
Broadcasting.
Eutelsat hopes to use new English language channels on its Hot Bird
satellite, due to be launched at the end of November, to reach UK viewers.
Dow Jones has decided to use the Eutelsat satellite for its 24-hours a day
European Business News, as has NBC SuperChannel, which is being revamped in
January to concentrate on business programming during the day.
Two new BBC channels to be launched early next year will also use Eutelsat.
They are to be run by the BBC in a joint venture with Pearson, owners of the
Financial Times. One will be a 24-hour television news channel, the other
entertainment.
Mr Giuliano Berretta, commercial director of Eutelsat, said: 'We are
concentrating on quality, free-to-air television.' Eutelsat is owned by the
main telephone organisations of Europe.
From early next year Eutelsat will have seven channels in English, including
MTV, Euronews and Eurosport as well as television channels in French and
Polish.
Eutelsat believes its channels are received on around 300,000 UK satellite
dishes.
At the end of June BSkyB said it had 3.45m subscribers - 74 per cent of them
on satellite dishes.
