<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / The European Pensions Ruling: Muted welcome from life
insurers - Some disappointment by Coloroll ruling / FT reporters analyse
yesterday's decisions of the European Court of Justice which are expected to
form a definitive framework under which employers and scheme trustees can
provide equal pensions for men and women
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some progress, but could have done better: UK life companies gave the court
judgments a muted welcome.
As life insurers sought to assimilate the implications of the rulings, it
was already clear that not all the questions on which they had been hoping
for decisions had been answered.
'It has removed a lot of the uncertainty, but we are not at the end of the
line,' was the comment from Standard Life.
Mr Peter Timberlake, marketing manager at Legal &amp; General, called for the
case to be incorporated into UK law through the pensions legislation which
is expected to be brought before parliament in the new session, in order to
give trustees of schemes a legal framework on which they could rely.
He believed there was such emphasis in the Coloroll judgment on defined
benefit pension schemes that there would need to be another case to settle
the position of money-purchase pension schemes. These are schemes where
money is invested annually on an employee's behalf.
Mr David Linnell, group actuary and compliance officer at Prudential
Corporation, expressed disappointment that the court did not appear to have
framed the Coloroll judgment in terms that would apply to all schemes. He
also said that aspects of the position for part-time workers were still
unclear.
There was some good news for life companies as trustees of insolvent schemes
are able to proceed to winding up the schemes. On winding up, most schemes
buy deferred annuities from insurance companies in order to pay out the same
level of benefits to current and potential pensioners.
</TEXT>
