<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Tight guard as Haiti MPs weigh amnesty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES HARDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A special session of Haiti's parliament, protected by US soldiers armed with
machine guns, got under way yesterday to consider an amnesty law for the
country's outgoing military regime.
The parliament had less than two hours' debate after a ceremonial opening,
and the business of drafting the amnesty law will resume today.
In a fresh burst of violence, a pro-democracy demonstrator was shot and
wounded by a Haitian paramilitary gunman just a few blocks from the
parliament building.
Witnesses said the man was shot in the chest as a crowd advanced towards the
headquarters of a paramilitary group. They said nervous members of the
paramilitary group, fearing the crowd was seeking revenge, fired to disperse
the demonstrators.
The Haitian legislature's meeting was the first in over a year, an
achievement that seemed to owe more to US efforts to secure the parliament
buildings and fly some exiled deputies into Port-au-Prince than the
resilience of the democratic institutions.
The Haitian deputies appeared deeply divided on whether to endorse a
wide-ranging amnesty for crimes committed by the regime that ousted
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide three years ago.
'I can't give an amnesty to assassins,' said one of 12 pro-Aristide senators
as he was flown in from Miami with an armed guard. But others said only a
broad amnesty would allow Haiti to move forward.
Crowds outside the barbed-wire-ringed parliament building were boisterous
and cheered returning deputies.
But inside the assembly, relations were strained. As Mr Jean-Louis Firmin,
president of the Senate and National Assembly, welcomed the return to
constitutional order and thanked President Bill Clinton for making the
re-opening of parliament possible, one deputy erupted: 'It is a shame. It is
a national embarrassment.'
The special session was convened by Mr Aristide, who is still in exile in
the US. The military leadership under General Raoul Cedras is expected to
step down once the law is passed, opening the way for Mr Aristide to return
to office.
The deployment of US troops around the parliament buildings was a sign of
the significance the Clinton administration is placing on the amnesty law,
which would not only mark the end of military rule but could pave the way
for reconciliation of Aristide supporters and Cedras loyalists.
The conspicuous US presence has led to criticism in the Haitian press that
the nation's democratic institutions are being violated. As a result, there
is to be no US army presence inside the chamber.
The 82-person Chamber of Deputies has not mustered the necessary 42 members
to achieve a quorum in 16 months, as many members were in exile or in
hiding.
President Aristide, in convening parliament, has called on the assembly to
debate not only the amnesty but also six other pieces of legislation,
including the separation of police and army powers.
Meanwhile, continued looting of humanitarian foodstores elsewhere in
Port-au-Prince was a further cause of concern to US officials yesterday. A
US embassy spokesman confirmed that the surge in pillaging showed the
breakdown of local policing. 'Clearly we are seeing some police stepping
back and letting the law and order situation evaporate,' he said.
</TEXT>
