<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Brussels pressure grows over networks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Karel Van Miert, EU commissioner responsible for competition policy, said
yesterday he was considering the use of special powers to force through the
liberalisation of alternative telecommunications infrastructure, such as
cable, energy and transport networks.
His announcement followed the failure of EU industry ministers to support
commission efforts to set a deadline by which member states would have to
throw open their networks to competition. The decision reflects growing
frustration within Brussels and certain member states at the slow pace in
embracing new information technology.
It is not yet clear that the commission will back Mr Van Miert's intention
to use so-called Article 90 powers to force the shake-up, which would allow
private operators to use alternative networks for the provision of services
already open to competition. This does not include 'voice' telephony, which
according to an earlier agreement, will not be opened up to competition
until January 1, 1998.
Yesterday Mr Van Miert said there was considerable support for the
liberalisation of alternative networks from member states, even if
significant differences remained over the liberalisation of traditional
telephone networks, most of which remain under monopoly control.
'We will push ahead with alternative infrastructures,' said Mr Van Miert.
'The proposals will be on the table by the time of the next telecoms council
meeting in November.'
Earlier, backed by Germany and the UK, Mr Martin Bangemann, commissioner
responsible for industry, failed to persuade member states that they should
set a deadline by which all existing networks should be deregulated and
private enterprises freed to build their own infrastructures.
Ministers from certain countries, notably Belgium and Spain, said they did
not want to discuss detail until the commission had presented a green paper
on liberalisation of infrastructures, expected by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
