FT  29 SEP 94 / Italian unions call for protests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italian trade union leaders yesterday called for countrywide protests in the
run-up to a general strike on October 14 against proposals in the 1995
budget. The date for the four-hour stoppage was confirmed yesterday in the
wake of Tuesday night's breakdown in talks between the government of Mr
Silvio Berlusconi and the unions over pension reform and spending cuts. Mr
Berlusconi, presenting the 1995 budget at a press conference yesterday,
described the general strike as 'an error' and insisted the budget had
sought to spread the burden of sacrifices fairly. However, Mr Berlusconi's
coalition partners, the populist Northern League, struck a discordant note
on pensions. A League statement dissociated itself from one of the most
controversial aspects of the government's pension reform - the reduction in
benefits for those retiring before the normal pensionable age, even though
they made the requisite contributions.
Mr Berlusconi also announced a new privatisation timetable yesterday. He
said Ilva, the state steel concern already partly privatised, and the
remains of SME, the foodstuffs group, would be sold off this year. By the
spring, the rest of INA, the insurance concern, would be sold. Stet, the
telecoms group, and Enel, the electricity authority, would be sold soon
after in the summer.
Stet profits up as state sell-off set for summer, Page 28
