<HEADLINE>
FT  29 SEP 94 / Tube strike looms as rail deal looks set to be accepted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The deal hammered out to settle the 15-week rail dispute is expected to win
overwhelming endorsement from the signal workers over the next two days.
But in a separate dispute members of the RMT transport union are still
threatening to bring London Underground to a halt for 24 hours tomorrow.
The package accepted by the union executive and negotiated with Railtrack,
the state-owned company that operates the network's infrastructure, is being
put to a telephone poll of union members today and tomorrow. The result is
expected tomorrow evening. The main points of the deal are:
an average increase in signalworkers' total earnings, including overtime and
supplements, of 8 per cent this year;
a 20 per cent average increase in basic rates;
a one-off lump sum payment averaging Pounds 480;
a further 2.5 per cent annual pay rise this year backdated to April.
The first three elements of the deal are linked to future productivity
improvements. They do not include any payments for past efficiencies, the
demand made by the union that led to the dispute.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said yesterday the deal was an
'excellent' one for the signal workers as well as being a 'sound investment
for Railtrack and the railway industry generally. It is a victory for the
steadfastness of the signal workers'.
Mr Robert Horton, Railtrack chairman, said he bitterly regretted it had
taken 'many weeks of needless strikes' before the deal had been achieved.
'At last we have reached an agreement to modernise the working practices in
the railway industry,' he said.
He questioned Mr Knapp's assertion that the signal workers would have an 8
per cent average increase in earnings. He claimed the actual figure was 3.4
per cent.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, transport secretary, also welcomed the agreement. He
said it was 'fully consistent with the government's approach to public
sector pay' as well as being self-financing and containable within
Railtrack's overall pay bill of just over Pounds 800m a year.
But as both sides were congratulating themselves on solving one transport
dispute, a new one loomed as the RMT executive was meeting yesterday evening
to discuss tomorrow's industrial action on the Underground.
The union is demanding a rise of at least 4 per cent for its Underground
members after they rejected a 2.5 per cent offer in a ballot. The other five
unions whose members work on the Underground have accepted the 2.5 per cent
offer.
Mr Knapp said no further talks were planned to try to resolve the dispute
and tomorrow's strike was likely to go ahead. However, London Underground
said it expected formal notification today from RMT that it was ready to
delay the strike to allow time to reach an accord.
Details and analysis, Page 10
Editorial Comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
