<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 94 / International Company News: GTE agrees Mexican telephone
venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GTE, the US telephone company, has agreed to form a joint venture with GF
Bancomer, Mexico's second largest financial group, and VISA, a large
industrial holding company, to provide telecommunications services in
Mexico.
The three companies have signed a letter of intent to form a company that
plans to apply for a long-distance telephone licence.
The long-distance monopoly enjoyed by Telefonos de Mexico, Mexico's national
carrier, expires in 1997, and Mexico's ministry of transport and
communications is expected to publish the regulations governing the
concession of new long-distance licences in the near future.
GTE joins MCI and Sprint, the two US long-distance carriers, in forming
joint ventures with Mexican partners to provide long-distance services from
1997.
MCI has formed an alliance with GF Banacci, Mexico's largest bank, and
Sprint with Iusacell, Mexico's largest non-Telmex cellular company.
