<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Acquisition helps lift Huntleigh 74% to
Pounds 5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Huntleigh Technology, the USM-quoted medical equipment manufacturer,
reported a 74 per cent increase in first half profits following a maiden
six-month contribution from Nesbit Evans.
Gains by the hospital bed manufacturer, acquired for Pounds 11.8m in
November last year, helped lift pre-tax profits from Pounds 3.03m to Pounds
5.27m in the six months to June 30.
Mr Rolf Schild, chairman, said the subsidiary - renamed Huntleigh Nesbit
Evans Healthcare - contributed about Pounds 1m to operating profits of
Pounds 5.21m (Pounds 2.86m).
The improvement was achieved on sharply increased turnover of Pounds 35.4m
(Pounds 16.3m), with the proportion of UK sales rising from 23 per cent to
50 per cent of the total following the Nesbit Evans deal.
Mr Schild, however, hinted that the full-year results might not show the
same growth.
'With the acquisition of Nesbit Evans, the consolidated profits are likely
to be weighted towards the first half owing to the seasonality of the UK
market,' he warned.
He also sounded a note of caution about overseas operations, particularly in
the US where there had been regulatory delays in winning FDA clearance for
some products.
Huntleigh's new French subsidiary made a loss following its launch late last
year, but Mr Schild said it was performing above initial expectations.
Earnings per share rose from 7.45p to 12.18p, and the board is lifting the
interim dividend to 2.75p (2p).
The shares closed up 5p at 433p.
</TEXT>
