<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 94 / Yeltsin offers upbeat message at US summit: Tension eases
over Bosnian arms embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Presidents Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin opened their fifth summit in 18
months yesterday with mutual proclamations that US-Russian relations had
never been better.
Mr Clinton told a large audience on the sunny south lawns of the White House
that the two countries were now partners not adversaries, adding, 'where we
do disagree, we can discuss our differences in a climate of warm peace, not
cold war'.
Mr Yeltsin was equally upbeat, saying it was 'all the more exciting for the
two countries to join hands'. Perhaps with an eye on his nationalist
opponents at home who have attacked his co-operation with the US, he
described the US as 'a strong partner and not an easy one to deal with -
just like Russia'.
One potential source of disagreement - not only with Russia but also with
Britain and France - was eased when Mr Clinton confirmed that the Bosnian
government had agreed to a delay of four to six months in the lifting of the
United Nations arms embargo against former Yugoslavia.
Bosnian president Alia Izetbegovic told the UN general assembly yesterday
that Bosnia wanted the continued presence over the winter of the UN
peacekeeping force, largely made up of British and French troops. Their
withdrawal would probably have followed the end of the embargo.
Mr Clinton had been under orders from Congress to seek a lifting of the arms
ban, unilaterally if necessary, by October 15 if the Bosnian Serbs refused
to sign the peace plan drawn up by the western contact group, which includes
Russia.
Mr Yeltsin said his reaction would be 'negative, of course' to any move to
rearm the Bosnians, but Mr Clinton was able to say that the question was now
'largely academic'.
The first of the Russian president's two days of talks centred on foreign
and security policy issues. The initial session with Mr Clinton lasted
throughout the morning rather than the planned 30 minutes, with Mr Yeltsin
reporting 'some pluses and some minuses'.
Mr Yeltsin then said at a State Department lunch: 'We do have to take
account of the special interests of our two states.' This was an apparent
reference to US reservations about Russian intervention in Nagorno-Karabakh
which featured prominently in the morning round.
A senior US official acknowledged later that Russia did have legitimate
interests in the enclave, but he added: 'So do the Armenians and the
Azeris.'
Although Mr Yeltsin signed an assortment of trade and investment agreements,
worth over Dollars 1bn (Pounds 630m) in the afternoon, today's talks will be
devoted principally to economic issues. Mr Yeltsin can expect pressure from
the US to quicken the pace of economic reform.
The US has gone to some lengths to create the right mood for this summit.
For the first time, Mr Yeltsin was staying at Blair House, the official
guest house, rather than the Russian Embassy. Yesterday afternoon a White
House ceremony honoured servicemen from both countries killed in the last
war, some recompense, in US eyes, for the exclusion of Russia from the D-Day
celebrations last June.
Wide relief over arms embargo, Page 3
Editorial Comment, Page 25
