<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 94 / Lobbyists to publish register of clients
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's top image-makers yesterday moved to polish their tarnished image
by announcing plans to strengthen the regulation of political lobbyists.
In a move that follows mounting controversy over the ways some MPs use
outside interests to supplement their parliamentary salaries, the public
relations industry is to introduce a detailed register of lobbyists and
their clients. Practitioners have made repeated calls for parliament to
regulate lobbying activities.
The industry is following the lead of the Association of Professional
Political Consultants. The association recently published its own code of
conduct for professional lobbyists.
The two organisations behind the latest move - the Public Relations
Consultants' Association and the Institute of Public Relations - yesterday
portrayed it as an attempt to make more information available about the
activities of lobbyists.
Both bodies - which represent practitioners and consultancies, some of whom
work as lobbyists - have added specific guidelines for political consultants
to their general codes of practice.
The initiative comes as a powerful House of Commons committee investigates
MPs' outside interests after newspaper revelations that two MPs were each
ready to put parliamentary questions to ministers in return for a payment of
Pounds 1,000.
The inquiry is expected to dissuade MPs from supplementing their salaries by
being directors or consultants to professional lobbying companies.
The political consultants' body already requires members not to 'place
themselves in a position of potential conflict of interest'.
The new register, which should be operating in eight weeks, will be updated
regularly and be available for not more than Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
