<HEADLINE>
FT  28 SEP 94 / Observer: Director's tonic
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is Glaxo about to get a grip on its legendary payouts to top directors?
Over the past two years it has paid or made provisions to pay more than
Pounds 17m to three outgoing directors. The big winner is chairman Sir Paul
Girolami, with Pounds 9.6m in pay, bonuses and pension contributions. Then
come Ernest Mario, former chief executive, with Pounds 5m, and Arthur
Pappas, head of Glaxo's Canadian and Latin American operations until this
year, with more than Pounds 2m.
Today's team members are comparative paupers. Mario's replacement is Sir
Richard Sykes, whose Pounds 930,000 pay package is one third less than
Mario's. The company is yet to name a non-executive chairman - there are
strong indications that the choice will be Sir Colin Corness, chairman of
Redland - at, say, Pounds 100,000 a year.
Even so, if any of the new boys slips off his perch or decides to take early
retirement, Glaxo shareholders deserve to know the potential scale of the
pay-offs before the event, rather than after.
</TEXT>
